": ["mim:131200", "mesh:D004715"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "endometriosis", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.999991774559021, "span": {"begin": 1160, "end": 1173}}, {"id": ["mim:608089", "mesh:D016889"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "endometrial cancer", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999980926513672, "span": {"begin": 1177, "end": 1195}}, {"id": ["mesh:D013256"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "steroid", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9848437905311584, "span": {"begin": 1238, "end": 1245}}, {"id": ["mesh:D011374"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "progesterone", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9995085000991821, "span": {"begin": 1256, "end": 1268}}, {"id": ["mesh:D011374"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "progesterone", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9957330822944641, "span": {"begin": 1353, "end": 1365}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:213"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "albumin", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9886565208435059, "span": {"begin": 1378, "end": 1385}}, {"id": ["mesh:D011374"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "progesterone", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.993493378162384, "span": {"begin": 1438, "end": 1450}}, {"id": ["mesh:D011374"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Progesterone", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9994078874588013, "span": {"begin": 1459, "end": 1471}}, {"id": ["mesh:D011374"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Progesterone", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9994686245918274, "span": {"begin": 1596, "end": 1608}}], "text": "Steroidogenesis starts with transport of cholesterol into the mitochondria. Cholesterol is converted to pregnenolone which can subsequently be converted to progesterone. The enzymatic step between pregnenolone and progesterone is catalysed by the 3-beta-hydroxysteroid dehydrogenase (3-beta-HSD enzyme). Progesterone can then either be converted into deoxycorticosterone to synthesize mineralocorticoids, or into its metabolite 17&alpha;-hydroxyprogesterone which may be converted into glucocorticoids or into androgens and subsequently, depending on circumstances, into estrogens (Bremer &amp; Miller, 2014; S et al., 2021; WL, 2017).&nbsp;  Other than being a precursor to several other downstream hormones, progesterone fulfills its role through the binding to its receptor, PGR. Mammalian progesterone receptors, which are nuclear receptors, are found in two main isoforms, PRA and PRB. Membrane bound progesterone receptors are also present in mammals (Brinton et al., 2008).&nbsp;  Progesterone signalling is known to be critical for maintenance of pregnancy, and its correct signalling is needed to prevent certain diseases linked to the uterus such as endometriosis or endometrial cancer (Wetendorf &amp; DeMayo, 2014). Like many steroid hormones, progesterone can be found bound or free. During the menstrual cycle for example, the majority of progesterone is bound to albumin (Westphal, 1986).&nbsp;  All these processes affect progesterone levels. Progesterone decrease can be due to disruption of upstream and downstream enzyme activity, but may also be affected by precursor levels. Progesterone decrease can therefore impact fertility, brain function and overall health.", "timestamp": "Fri May 15 21:45:58 +0000 2026"}